                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1383">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.52/224.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Special
                        Agent <persName type="to">Carothers</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-04-11T20:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 11, 1914, 8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your April 9, 7 p.m., regarding interests of nationals of foreign powers other
                    than the United States. Ascertain, if possible, who have been Carranza’s
                    advisers in connection with this matter.</p>
                <p>Department infers Carranza is being advised by competent international lawyers,
                    and if so hopes that its instructions of March 2, through Consul Simpich, copy
                    of which went to American Consul, Juarez, which reflects Department’s position,
                    will be seriously studied before a definite position is assumed by the
                    Constitutionalists.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
